== 4...b5 · Caro variation ==
Black drives White's bishop away. Black ends White's pressure on their knight, therefore ends the possibility of Bxc6 and makes their e5 pawn more secure. 

While ...b5 is a common move in Ruy Lopez at some point, it is unusual to play it immediately on move four, because Black's e5 pawn was still defended tactically (Bxc6 dxc6 Nxe5 Qd4! forks White's knight and e4 pawn). 

[[/5. Bb3|'''5. Bb3''']] is the only move. White preserves their bishop and gets the free tempo to move it onto the dangerous a2-g8 long diagonal, eying Black's vulnerable f7 pawn. 

=== History ===
4...b5 made early appearances in the mid-19th century. [[wikipedia:Charles Henry Stanley|Charles Henry Stanley]] (1819―1901) played it with Black against [[wikipedia:Eugène Rousseau (chess player)|Eugène Rousseau]] (1805―1870) in New Orleans in 1845, with the continuation 5. Bb3 Nf6.<ref>[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1001226 Eugene Rosseau vs Charles Stanley, 1845. Chessgames.com]</ref> The Graz variation, with 5. Bb3 Bc5, was also common, as played against [[wikipedia:Paul Morphy|Morphy]] in an 1859 consultation game.<ref>[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1258277 Paul Morphy vs Allies, 1859. Chessgames.com]</ref> 

4...b5 is named after [[wikipedia:Horatio Caro|Horatio Caro]] (1862―1920), the British-German chess master known for the [[Chess Opening Theory/1. e4/1...c6|Caro-Kann defence]], who played it from the 1880s. He introduced the continuation 5. Bb3 Bb7 and would play by fianchettoing both bishops.<ref>[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=2753336 Gustave Simonson vs Horatio Caro, 1887. Chessgames.com]</ref><ref>[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1462460 Jackson Showalter vs Horatio Caro, 1898. Chessgames.com]</ref><ref>[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1462452 Geza Maroczy vs Horatio Caro, 1898. Chessgames.com]</ref>

The modern mainline continuation, 5. Bb3 Na5, was played by the likes of [[wikipedia:Mark Taimanov|Mark Taimanov]] and others,<ref>e.g. [https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1128320 Boris Spassky vs Mark Taimanov, 1955. Chessgames.com]</ref> but received the '''Norwegian''' soubriquet for [[wikipedia:Svein Johannessen|Svein Johannessen]] (1937―2007), a Norwegian IM who adopted the line.<ref>e.g. [https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1044243 Bobby Fischer vs Svein Johannessen, 1966. Chessgames.com]</ref>

